"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多债券专栏</h4><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/these-chirping-sounds-can-soothe-your-anxiety-7bb6e809?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">鸟类是对抗焦虑的秘密武器</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/float-tanks-health-benefits-stress-d844e4ba?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">当寻找你的幸福意味着漂浮、赤裸时</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/celebrating-mothers-day-after-your-mom-is-gone-af4b84d6?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">当你悲伤时应对母亲节</a></li></ul></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/put-great-sex-on-your-vacation-to-do-list-198da577</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/put-great-sex-on-your-vacation-to-do-list-198da577<author><![CDATA[Elizabeth Bernstein]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>IWE过滤器</category><category>个人公告</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>伊威过滤器</category><category>个人公告</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Miami Sees Its First Population Drop in Decades]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>尽管经济繁荣，住房成本飙升仍驱使许多当地人离开<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823690/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="迈阿密戴德县的人口在 2019 年至 2022 年间出现萎缩，这是至少自 1970 年以来多年来首次出现人口减少。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>迈阿密戴德县人口在 2019 年至 2022 年间出现萎缩，这是至少自 1970 年以来多年来首次出现人口减少。 Saul Martinez/Bloomberg News <span>Saul Martinez/Bloomberg News</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098188"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098188"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/konrad-putzier" itemprop="url" rel="author">康拉德·普齐尔</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/deborah-acosta" itemprop="url" rel="author">黛博拉·阿科斯塔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/miami-sees-its-first-population-drop-in-decades-e181171f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>迈阿密是一个雄心勃勃地成为商业和金融中心的全球热点，但它正在赶走的居民多于吸引的居民。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/miami-locals-are-steamed-over-relocating-new-yorkers-driving-up-apartment-rents-11652175000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">不断上涨的住房成本</a>和变化无常的劳动力市场（从某种角度来看，劳动力市场尚未从疫情中恢复过来）正在迫使许多当地人逃离家园。根据布鲁金斯学会对<a href="https://www.brookings.edu/articles/pandemic-driven-population-declines-in-large-urban-areas-are-slowing-or-reversing-latest-census-data-shows/" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国人口普查局数据的分析</a>，2020 年至 2022 年间，迈阿密戴德郡因净移民到佛罗里达州其他地区或其他州而失去了 79,535 人。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826058?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>尽管外国移民抵消了部分损失，并帮助该县的人口去年略有增加，但迈阿密戴德县的人口在 2019 年至 2022 年间仍然出现萎缩，根据美国联邦储备银行的数据，这是至少自 1970 年以来多年来首次出现人口减少。圣路易斯。</p><p>该州最大县的人口流失与佛罗里达州其他地区形成鲜明对比，后者在 2021 年至 2022 年间新增人口比任何其他州都多。</p><p>根据在线挂牌网站<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/Z" class="">Zillow 的</a>数据<span class="company-name-type">，</span>自 2020 年 6 月以来，迈阿密的房价已飙升 53%，在 50 个大都市房地产市场中排名第二，仅次于坦帕。数据公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CSGP" class="">CoStar</a>的数据显示，自 2019 年以来，租金中位数上涨了 27% <span class="company-name-type">，</span>尽管由于经济适用房长期短缺而导致人口减少，但租金中位数仍在上涨。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826059?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>很容易发现这座城市蓬勃发展的方式。主要大道上散落着建筑起重机，迈阿密办公楼的空置率低于美国其他主要城市。迈阿密戴德县的失业率远低于全国平均水平，并且正在以有史以来最快的速度创造新企业。</p><p>但迈阿密面临着与美国金融和科技中心纽约市和旧金山相同的风险，那里高薪白领工作的增长提高了生活成本，导致许多城市的工薪阶层和中产阶级居民流离失所。寻找更实惠的居住地。</p><p>尽管经济繁荣，但迈阿密戴德县在总人口中所占的比例在两年内比巴尔的摩市和密歇根州韦恩县（包括底特律）经历了更大的损失。</p><p> “这是中产阶级，是我们的人才基础，是我们的大学毕业生到其他地方寻找更好的机会，”佛罗里达国际大学豪尔赫·M·佩雷斯大都会中心人口普查信息中心负责人玛丽亚·伊尔切瓦说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823731?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2020 年至 2022 年间，迈阿密-戴德县因净移民到佛罗里达州其他地区或其他州而失去了 79,535 人。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的詹姆斯·杰克曼</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>何塞·佩雷斯,</p>一位在迈阿密出生和长大的房地产经纪人是那些感到房价过高的人之一。当生活成本开始飙升时，他一半以上的客户离开了该地区。他说，他们的收入在 70,000 美元到 150,000 美元之间，靠工资生活。<p></p><p>佩雷斯很快就自己搬了出去。他以 80 万美元的价格卖掉了迈阿密的房屋，并以 29.7 万美元的价格在佛罗里达州中部城市奥卡拉购买了一套类似的房屋。他说，仅保险方面的节省每年就高达 5,460 美元。他的财产税从每年 7000 美元降到了不到 2000 美元。</p><p> “在这里你可以看到<span class="company-name-type">，</span>你花的钱可以得到更多的回报，”佩雷斯说，他现在为国家住宅建筑商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DHI" class="">DR Horton</a>工作。</p><p>在大流行之前，迈阿密已经是该国负担能力最差的大都市区之一，这进一步推高了房价。根据美国劳工统计局的数据，迈阿密都市区 6 月份的年度消费者价格通胀率为 6.9%。这是全国通货膨胀率的两倍多。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1000" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826060?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>纽约市的“负担得起的租房者”比例也是所有主要都市区中最高的：根据联合中心今年发布的一份报告，61%的租房人口将家庭收入的30%或更多的钱花在住房上。哈佛大学住房研究。</p><p>高租金令人痛苦，因为该地区的小时工资虽然有所上涨，但截至 2022 年仍低于全国平均水平，与纽约和旧金山的收入相去甚远。</p><p>虽然失业率较低，但该县的劳动力市场在某种程度上落后于该州其他地区。佛罗里达州经济机会部的数据显示，迈阿密戴德县 5 月份的就业总人数略低于 2019 年的水平，而整个佛罗里达州的就业总人数有所增加。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823506?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">施工人员正在迈阿密的 Legacy Residences 开发项目中工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的斯科特·麦金太尔</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>该地区无法与纽约等城市的多元化经济基础相媲美，而迈阿密在吸引工厂和大型企业总部方面也难以与菲尼克斯和奥斯汀等阳光地带新兴城市相媲美，这些工厂和大型企业总部带来了数千个就业机会。</p><p>迈阿密吸引了大量新公司。根据美国人口普查局的数据，2022 年，迈阿密戴德县收到了 127,895 份商业申请。这比去年略有下降，但远高于大流行前的水平。</p><p>但许多科技和金融公司正在开设雇用人数很少的小型办公室或卫星办公室。其他人则<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/miamis-love-affair-with-crypto-is-souring-as-bitcoin-faithful-flock-to-the-city-9244f0d9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">专注于加密货币</a>，这个市场已经暴跌。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为迈阿密的未来前景如何？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>有限的公共交通和拥挤的道路也使得吸引雇主变得困难。根据数据公司 INRIX 的数据，2021 年至 2022 年间，迈阿密因交通延误损失的时间增加了 59%，是美国大城市中增幅最高的城市之一。</p><p> “我们需要成为一座在天际线以下能够提供良好生活质量的城市，”伊尔切瓦说。</p><p>尽管如此，仍有乐观的理由。富裕居民的涌入和房价上涨正在增加税收收入，而近期新建筑的激增可能会随着时间的推移降低住房成本。租金增长放缓，工资上涨。</p><p> 2022 年，外国移民数量从疫情期间的低点开始增加，并帮助抵消了部分美国人的外流，尽管从 2020 年到 2022 年，尽管海外新居民有所增加，迈阿密戴德县的人口仍减少了 21,664 人。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823507?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">数据公司 INRIX 的数据显示，2021 年至 2022 年间，迈阿密因交通延误而损失的时间增加了 59%。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔·雷德尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一些离开的迈阿密居民享受着较低的生活成本，但被迫做出其他权衡。娜塔莉·佩纳 (Natalie Pena) 和她的丈夫以 44 万美元的价格出售了他们在迈阿密 1,100 平方英尺的房屋。六月，他们带着儿子搬到了奥卡拉的一所更大的房子，他们以大约一半的价格购买了这套房子。</p><p>尽管如此，她在找工作方面还是遇到了一些困难。她的丈夫是一名理发师，每周三早 4.5 小时通勤到迈阿密，为客户提供服务直到周五晚上。 “我原以为会受到打击，工资会减少，但这有点令人震惊，”她说。</p><p>迈阿密戴德县市长去年宣布出现住房危机，并推出了多项经济适用住房举措和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/miami-offers-interest-free-loans-to-condo-owners-53189e9f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">其他计划</a>。州长<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">罗恩·德桑蒂斯</a>最近签署了一项立法，将激励开发商在全州范围内建设劳动力和经济适用房，以帮助解决住房危机。该法律被称为“当地生活法案”，还禁止地方市政当局实施租金管制。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1200" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826895?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> 1970 年至 2010 年间，迈阿密戴德县的人口翻了一番，但过去十年增长放缓。伊尔切瓦说，起初，来自国外的移民掩盖了该地区的人口流动。疫情期间资金外流的增加加上移民的减少，导致该地区的人口结构出现赤字。</p><p>根据LinkedIn最近的一项研究，离开迈阿密地区的专业人士的首选目的地是奥兰多、坦帕湾、亚特兰大和杰克逊维尔——所有城市都气候温暖、税收低，但住房便宜得多。</p><p>当地居民、牛虻纪录片制作人比利·科本 (Billy Corben) 经常批评当地政客推动快速发展的做法，他说：“建造这座城市的人们住不起他们一生都居住在其中的房子。” “一旦那些人走了，那么迈阿密是什么？这个地方还剩下什么？” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823691?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">迈阿密众多在建建筑之一的 55 区工地。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的斯科特·麦金太尔</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 Konrad Putzier <a href="mailto:konrad.putzier@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（konrad.putzier@wsj.com）</a>和 Deborah Acosta（ <a href="mailto:deborah.acosta@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">deborah.acosta@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/miami-sees-its-first-population-drop-in-decades-e181171f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/miami-sees-its-first-population-drop-in-decades-e181171f<author><![CDATA[Konrad PutzierDeborah Acosta]]></author><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人口统计</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人口统计</category><category>房地产</category><category>财产</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Science of Spin’ Review: The World in a Whirligig]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>从很早开始，人类的关键发明就涉及旋转：磨石、陶轮、跑步机、泵。然而，车轮被高估了。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590112630365408848"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826991?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿拉米库存照片</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590112630365408848"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">詹姆斯·B·梅格斯</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日下午 6:19 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-science-of-spin-review-the-world-in-a-whirligig-6de2c75d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>不少作者通过从单一主题的角度审视广泛的历史、思想或科学的书籍获得了成功。这一趋势可能始于詹姆斯·格莱克 (James Gleick) 的《混沌》(Chaos) (1987)，该书探讨了随机性在自然界中令人惊讶的作用。不太抽象的是，马克·库尔兰斯基（Mark Kurlansky）在《鳕鱼》（Cod）（1997 年）中采用了紧密聚焦的方法，而玛丽·罗奇（Mary Roach）在《僵硬》（Stiff）（2003 年）中采取了一种紧密关注的方法，这本书是一本关于尸体的书。</p><p>罗兰·恩诺斯 (Roland Ennos) 在《旋转科学》中将这种方法提升到了令人眼花缭乱的高度。很多东西都会旋转——从玩具陀螺到飓风——的想法可能看起来很平淡。但赫尔大学生物科学教授恩诺斯先生希望我们明白自旋是基础。它在我们身体的功能和基础设施的设计中发挥着重要作用。当然，它也可以在我们星球乃至宇宙的有序运动中找到。恩诺斯先生希望《旋转的科学》能让读者“最终能够理解世界运转的真正原因”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/84d92765-15f6-4564-8af6-e53178e52e85.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>他首先讲述了英国工程师在第一次世界大战期间设计突破性的索普威思骆驼双翼飞机时如何低估了旋转的力量。在传统飞机中，电机安装在机身上，并旋转一端带有螺旋桨的轴。在骆驼中，轴被锁定在机身上，而整个电机以及连体螺旋桨猛烈旋转。这种奇怪的设计有几个优点和一个很大的缺点：发动机巨大的旋转力往往会让没有经验的飞行员陷入快速的死亡螺旋。</p><p>恩诺斯先生告诫读者不要轻视自旋物理学，然后将他的故事大致倒回到时间的开始。我们了解大爆炸如何“在其产生的气体云中形成巨大的漩涡”。漩涡是恒星、星系和其他所有物体形成的核心。 “自旋，”他写道，“正是我们的宇宙存在的原因。”</p><p>恩诺斯先生努力说服我们——除了索普威思骆驼事件——要感谢我们的宇宙有如此多的旋转。混乱的气体云只有通过旋转才能演化成我们有序的太阳系。我们特别幸运的是我们的家园星球以正确的速度旋转。它的自转形成了地球的磁层，使我们免受致命的太阳辐射的影响。在地球表面，从大气到洋流的一切似乎都处于旋转状态，不断地混合和搅动过程，从而调节温度、降低风速并调节降雨量。简而言之，旋转使世界成为“一个奇妙的居住地”。</p><p>当恩诺斯先生描述历史上人类的繁荣在很大程度上涉及利用旋转的力量时，他真的很兴奋。我们了解旧石器时代的人们如何使用弓钻（可以通过松散的弓快速旋转的木轴）来生火、钻制造工具所需的孔，甚至进行简单的牙科治疗。寻找新的纺织方法使早期文明成为可能：将棉和羊毛纤维缠绕成线使我们开始穿着织物而不是动物皮毛。早在工业革命之前，人类的重要发明通常都涉及旋转：磨石、陶轮、跑步机和各种泵。</p><p>恩诺斯先生的故事并不是简单的科技必胜主义。逆向投资者尤其会喜欢他对他所谓的“平庸之轮”的描述。人们常常将轮子的发明视为改变世界的创新的典范。恩诺斯先生说，事实上，在人类历史的大部分时间里，轮子——至少是用于运输的轮子——并没有那么有用。在工程道路发展之前，地面太崎岖，轮式交通无法比步行或骑马有多大改善。恩诺斯指出，印加人、玛雅人和阿兹特克人创造了四轮滚动的玩具，但他们从未创造过成人尺寸的版本。如果没有金属工具，就不可能用木头制造耐用的轮子。</p><p>随着工业革命的到来，恩诺斯先生的叙述节奏加快了。水轮为轧棉机和织机提供动力，涡轮机旋转得更快。蒸汽机作为一种日益移动的动力源逐年发展，直到蒸汽被柴油和汽油取代。试图跟上可能会让一些读者头晕目眩。</p><p>恩诺斯先生的最后几章探讨了人类在工作和休闲中体现旋转力学的方式。我们看到投手和高尔夫球手在将尽可能多的能量释放到他们投入的球中之前是如何结束的。恩诺斯先生希望我们将人体理解为一种机器，具有放大旋转力的铰链和杠杆。他说，我们的“复杂的关节机构”在很多方面都优于机械系统。</p><p> 《旋转的科学》进展太快，以至于无法花太多时间去了解故事背后的人。例如，当恩诺斯先生讨论花样滑冰时（这项运动似乎除了旋转之外什么都没有），他详细分析了当滑冰运动员拉动手臂以加速旋转时会发生什么。物理学很有趣。但人们希望他采访了一位花样滑冰运动员并询问：感觉如何？</p><p>恩诺斯先生最后哀叹许多科学家缺乏“对自旋科学的直觉”。他说，当他们应该从密切观察开始时，他们经常转向方程来模拟旋转物体的行为。他认为，应该给学生更多的时间来尝试陀螺仪和陀螺仪。这些简单的玩具可以让我们了解宇宙美丽平衡、动态的本质。而且，无论我们是扔飞盘还是设计飞机，我们都应该花一点时间来欣赏。</p><p><em>梅格斯先生是《大众力学》的前编辑，也是曼哈顿研究所的高级研究员。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:19:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-science-of-spin-review-the-world-in-a-whirligig-6de2c75d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-science-of-spin-review-the-world-in-a-whirligig-6de2c75d<category>纺织品</category><category>服装/纺织品</category><category>消费品</category><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category><category>纺织品</category><category>衣服</category><category>消费品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Utopia’ by Travis Scott Review: Leaning In to Hip-Hop Spectacle]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位艺术家自 2018 年以来的首张专辑是说唱日历上的一个高潮，其特点是迷幻的声音、他标志性的歌声以及 Beyoncé、Drake 和 The Weeknd 等主要嘉宾。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590122123270646584"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826622?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">特拉维斯·斯科特在迈阿密表演</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Getty Images for E11EVEN </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590122123270646584"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">马克·理查森</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日下午 5:42 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/utopia-by-travis-scott-review-leaning-in-to-hip-hop-spectacle-1ea47138"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉维斯·斯科特 (Travis Scott) 早在 2021 年他的家乡休斯敦 Astroworld 音乐节发生悲剧之前就已经是说唱界的一个有争议的人物了，当时他的演出期间发生了人群挤压事件，导致 10 人死亡、数百人受伤。尽管斯科特先生（1991 年出生，原名雅克·韦伯斯特）非常受欢迎，拥有两张排名第一的录音室专辑和四张排名第一的单曲，但他的快速崛起经常受到嘻哈爱好者的怀疑，他们认为他的音乐很轻松内容上，他的歌词没什么可说的。他通过视频做出了混乱的道歉，似乎与情况的严重性不相符，因此他对演唱会灾难的反应进一步受到批评，考虑到他在台上鼓励歌迷的热情，一些人认为他负有个人责任。尽管这位说唱歌手从未被正式指控有不当行为，但自那以后的两年里，他一直保持低调，为其他艺术家的一些单曲做出了贡献。</p><p>上周，斯科特先生的第四张录音室专辑《Utopia》（Cactus Jack/Epic）的宣布和发行，以及他 2018 年热门唱片《Astroworld》的后续专辑，一切都发生了变化。他的时机很好。到目前为止，2023 年嘻哈音乐的“事件”记录还很短缺，正如《滚石》杂志 7 月初报道的那样，对于这一流派来说，今年是排行榜上表现疲弱的一年。斯科特先生有机会单枪匹马地改变叙事，推出一张史诗般的专辑，无论是在内容上（长达 73 分钟，对于嘻哈唱片来说相当长），还是在明星云集的嘉宾名单上。 《乌托邦》被刻意塑造成一部大片，每一个该类型的粉丝都被迫参与其中。虽然它不会改变那些质疑斯科特写作技巧的人的想法，但它始终是一个强大且偶尔令人兴奋的歌曲集。</p><p>斯科特先生的两大资产是他的制作品味和声音的共鸣。自从他的职业生涯开始，他就对具有实验性的摇滚和流行艺术家表达了钦佩，比如 Björk 和 Radiohead，而《Utopia》和之前的《Astroworld》一样，充满了丰富的迷幻节拍。尽管唱片中出现了数十位制作人、词曲作者和客座歌手，但斯科特先生和录音室合作者，包括迈克·迪恩（坎耶·韦斯特、The Weeknd），已将这些作品组合成一个连贯的整体。</p><p>第一首曲目“Hyaena”以颤抖的贝斯线和鼓声拉开序幕，听起来就像一群牛踩在被砸碎的钢门上，在斯科特先生毫不费力的高速说唱之后，它以 Funkadelic 的“”的样本结束。蛆脑。”另一个早期亮点“Modern Jam”由 Guy-Manuel de Homem-Christo 制作，他更广为人知的是 Daft Punk 的一半，流畅的极简节奏是 Scott 先生旋律诗句的完美背景。这首歌是一首《我回来了！》声明中，他并没有说任何特别深刻的话——“知道我已经一年没见过路了/让我进去就像我在假释中一样”是一句有代表性的对联——但《现代果酱》名副其实。 。</p><p>虽然斯科特作为逐行作词家和故事讲述者的局限性是显而易见的，但他的声音是本世纪说唱界最独特的声音之一。它既沙哑又略带鼻音，既是一种深沉的物理声音，又非常适合电子处理。这种组合给斯科特先生的说唱带来了未来主义的光泽，即使你听几年前的歌曲，他也总是给人一种“新”的印象。也就是说，他在说唱时往往会走马观花，并经常做出最明显的选择。在第五次剪辑《上帝的国度》中，这意味着要说出“去泰德·邦迪，然后回家扮演阿尔·邦迪”这样的台词，这些台词既笨拙又没有什么特别的意义。</p><p>尽管这样的抱怨经常出现在《乌托邦》中，但这张专辑的声音奇迹提供了平衡。华丽的“My Eyes”以 Bon Iver 的 Justin Vernon 的声音和故障电子设备为特色，还有深情的英国歌手 Sampha 的同样出色的客串，这首歌传达了悲伤的放弃。险恶的“Meltdown”，以 Drake 的开场说唱，具有渐进式结构，感觉就像三首歌合二为一，从怪异的弦乐样本到说唱子流派练习的厚重低音咆哮，最后以弹奏原声的尾声结束吉他。碧昂丝以一首快速说唱拉开轻快爵士乐《Delresto (Echoes)》的序幕，然后在斯科特先生加入她的同时开始唱歌，而弗农先生再次献声。</p><p>说唱音乐在排行榜上步履蹒跚的原因之一是地区性的音乐风潮一直在上升。如今的嘻哈音乐是一种碎片化且快速发展的流派，根据地理和共同的审美观而有无数的变化，而且很多音乐都是年轻人在家里创作的。 《乌托邦》很有趣，部分原因是它有力地反对了低保真趋势。这是一部高度精致和复杂的制作，可能需要一些昂贵的工作室费用，更不用说像 Weeknd、SZA 和 21 Savage 这样的大牌制作的成本。是的，它太长了，最终没有太多可说的，但如果你开着长途车，把“Utopia”调大声，你就会明白为什么我们可能会在公共场所听到它的音乐好几个月了。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。理查森是《华尔街日报》的摇滚和流行音乐评论家。在 Twitter 上关注他@MarkRichardson。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 21:42:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/utopia-by-travis-scott-review-leaning-in-to-hip-hop-spectacle-1ea47138</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/utopia-by-travis-scott-review-leaning-in-to-hip-hop-spectacle-1ea47138<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>活动日历</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>IWE过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>活动日历</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>伊威过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Catering to Your Midlife Crisis Is a Growing Business]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>新兴行业帮助那些寻求充实的第二幕的成年人<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086694"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824308?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">寿命的延长导致更多的人在 40 多岁、50 多岁和 60 多岁时寻找有意义的追求。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：iStock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086694"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-tergesen" itemprop="url" rel="author">安妮·特格森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日上午 10:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/midlife-crisis-money-business-companies-29dc2273"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国人希望他们的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-virtuous-midlife-crisis-11578830400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中年危机</a>变得更有成效。这为越来越多的公司、教练和顾问提供了数百万美元的机会。</p><p>有些程序是在线的，收费几百美元。其他活动则在异国情调的地点进行，提供豪华住宿、瑜伽和冲浪课程，费用为数千美元。有时会有折扣。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/death-finances-and-how-many-of-us-get-our-money-needs-wrong-51a660a2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更长的寿命</a>为企业提供了动力，引导更多的人在 40 多岁、50 多岁和 60 多岁时寻找有意义的追求。一些心理学家将这一时期称为第二次成年期，在此期间，从行政人员到全职父母再到照顾者等身份塑造角色可能会消失，导致一些人重新评估。</p><p>现代老年学院 (MEA) 联合创始人奇普·康利 (Chip Conley) 表示：“在这个寿命越来越长、变化越来越大的时代，过渡是我们需要掌握的一项技能。”该学院提供在线和面对面研讨会。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824307?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">现代老年学院联合创始人奇普·康利 (Chip Conley) 身穿白衬衫，他表示，年龄歧视会让中年人认为自己无关紧要。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：现代长者学院</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一些研究表明，生活满意度在 40 多岁左右达到低点，这可能是因为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-life-balance-is-their-second-priority-work-is-their-first-b069aeee?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">工作和家庭需求</a>带来的压力。这种权衡，加上<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/would-life-be-better-if-you-worked-less-3f49e69a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">很少的时间进行自我反思</a>，让许多人不确定如何迎接他们的下一个篇章。</p><p>康利说，中年课程的讲师探讨的主题包括中年心理发展和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/anti-ageism-workplace-language-biggest-school-district-368db30f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">年龄歧视</a>，这可能会让人们相信自己“无关紧要，已经过时了，最好的时光已经过去了”。</p><p>他在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ABNB" class="">Airbnb</a>工作后创建了 MEA <span class="company-name-type">，</span>这家家庭共享公司的年轻创始人称他 52 岁为现代长者。研讨会旨在帮助参与者学习更好地应对压力过渡， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/layoffs-tech-job-cuts-fired-survival-guide-how-to-get-hired-laid-off-employees-11667943893?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">包括裁员</a>、离婚和亲人去世。</p><h3>自我反思的空间</h3><p>与一些大学<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-60-000-these-colleges-help-older-workers-plot-encore-careers-a0060b9a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">为接近职业生涯结束的成年人</a>推出的为期数月的学术课程一样，大多数中年课程都以 8 到 50 人为一组。</p><p> “这些项目为人们提供了空间和结构，不仅可以考虑他们在这个阶段想做什么，还可以考虑成为谁，”芭芭拉·瓦克斯曼说，</p>一位在 MEA 任教的老年学家。<p></p><p> 46 岁的纳迪亚·阿尔·亚法伊 (Nadia Al Yafai) 表示，她最近从一家英国保险公司的高级职位被解雇后，发现了 Midlife ReThink，这是一个价值 385 美元的在线计划。</p><p>她说，“中年反思”被证明具有变革性，并补充说，遇到其他同样感到无依无靠的人让她感到安慰。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824305?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Midlife ReThink 为寻求新方向的人们提供在线课程，其中一张幻灯片概述了人生的各个阶段。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：中年反思</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>该计划由专门研究劳动力性别和代际平衡的教练兼顾问 Avivah Wittenberg-Cox 于 2020 年发起，包括三个 90 分钟的在线课程，约有 25 名参与者。</p><p> “很多人都在经历自己的转变，就好像他们正在经历一些可怕的事情一样，”维滕伯格-考克斯说。 “Community is the key to helping people realize it&#39;s normal and fairly predictable at this age and stage to get restless” and crave change, she said.</p><p> Al Yafai said an exercise that asked her to define what she wants from the next seven years led her to start a consulting business.</p><p> “I went from feeling a bit lost at not being part of my old world anymore to realizing there&#39;s this new world of people doing really interesting things,” she said.</p><h3> &#39;We still have value&#39;</h3><p> Reboot Partners, which provides workshops and coaching on career and other transitions, has organized two weekend-long retreats this year, in Santa Fe, NM, and Sag Harbor, NY, for $1,895. Participants visualize their perfect life and discuss fears and motivations around change, said co-founder Jaye Smith. </p><p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824304?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Modern Elder Academy&#39;s virtual and in-person workshops held at its campus in Mexico aim to help participants better navigate stressful transitions.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Modern Elder Academy</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> On an oceanfront campus in Mexico&#39;s Baja California Sur, MEA teaches courses on re-creating careers, embracing midlife and optimizing longevity. It also offers weekslong online programs on transitions, purpose and reframing retirement for $395 to $1,250. It plans to open a campus in Santa Fe, NM, next year.</p><p> Lisa Fitzpatrick said MEA, which she first attended in 2019, helped her face down barriers to success.</p><p> Dr. Fitzpatrick, 55, was launching Grapevine Health, which publishes online health information for low-income communities. She relished the opportunity to interact with Conley, a veteran entrepreneur.</p><p> The Washington, DC, resident said an exercise to identify self-limiting beliefs helped her conquer a fear of being too old to start a business. She returned to Baja five times to attend workshops on entrepreneurship and healthcare. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824306?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Lisa Fitzpatrick says attending Modern Elder Academy helped her confront her barriers to success.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ron Ceaser</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For that first visit, she received a scholarship for a seven-day stay that now costs $4,000 to $5,500.</p><p> One exercise Fitzpatrick particularly enjoys involves stacking rocks on the beach. “It sounds kind of woo-woo,” she said. But the task of balancing a big rock on a small one helped her overcome mental barriers to what she could achieve. “MEA helps people in midlife realize we still have value,” she said.</p><h3> Finding a purpose</h3><p> Some programs explore next acts or spirituality.</p><p> Dallas-based Halftime Institute&#39;s offerings include a two-day, $2,500 couples retreat and a $25,000 yearlong program. The latter features in-person and online sessions, as well as one-on-one coaching on relationships, health, faith and finding one&#39;s calling.</p><p> “Not everyone who goes through it is Christian but that&#39;s the perspective we come from,” said Co-Chief Executive Jim Stollberg. “We talk about a calling, rather than a purpose.”</p><p> For $2,500, Union Theological Seminary in New York offers a four-month Encore Transition program, with virtual sessions on topics such as spirituality in midlife and finding work with social purpose.</p><p> Consultant Carolyn Buck Luce leads a group of women through a weekslong online program called the Decade Game that costs $2,250. It challenges participants to set goals to guide their next decade in areas including education and purpose.</p><p> “It&#39;s about being able to declare the purpose you were called to,” said Luce.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How are you navigating midlife?加入下面的对话。</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/b28e0b44-8140-466a-922c-df1aa6d8aa70.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Write to Anne Tergesen at <a href="mailto:anne.tergesen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anne.tergesen@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/midlife-crisis-money-business-companies-29dc2273</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/midlife-crisis-money-business-companies-29dc2273<author><![CDATA[Anne Tergesen]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Career Planning/Management</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>Retirement Planning</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>career planning</category><category> management</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>retirement planning </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Local Malls, Stuck in ‘Death Spiral,’ Plunge in Value]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Crystal Mall in Connecticut, worth $150 million in 2012, recently sold for $9.5 million <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823519/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="The cut-rate sales price of Crystal Mall in Waterford, Conn., shows how fast the fortunes of U.S. regional malls have fallen in recent years." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> The cut-rate sales price of Crystal Mall in Waterford, Conn., shows how fast the fortunes of US regional malls have fallen in recent years. Johnny Milano/Bloomberg News <span>Johnny Milano/Bloomberg News</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093483"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093483"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kate-king" itemprop="url" rel="author">Kate King</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> WATERFORD, Conn.—Crystal Mall&#39;s parking lots used to be so crowded that parents would line up to drop off their teenagers near one of the entrances rather than search for a spot.</p><p> Now, the vast stretches of cracked pavement surrounding this 1980s-era regional mall on Connecticut&#39;s coast have more weeds than cars. Valued by an appraiser at $153 million as recently as 2012, Crystal Mall sold in June for just over $9.5 million in a foreclosure auction.</p><p> “To look at it now, it&#39;s disheartening,” said Waterford&#39;s top elected leader, First Selectman Rob Brule, who grew up in this working-class town and described the mall as the social centerpiece of his youth.</p><p> Crystal Mall&#39;s cut-rate sales price shows how rapidly the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/shopping-mall-nostalgia-auction-420a44f9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">value of America&#39;s regional malls</a> has deteriorated in recent years due to changing shopping habits, competition from other retail and the rise of online shopping.</p><p> Older, low-end malls are worth at least 50% and in some cases more than 70% less than they were when mall valuations peaked in late 2016, said Vince Tibone, head of US retail and industrial research for real-estate research firm Green Street.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Now, as more than $14 billion of loans backed by these properties comes due in the next 12 months, according to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MCO" class="company-name">Moody&#39;s</a> Analytics, struggling malls are defaulting on their debt. With mortgage rates up sharply, refinancing that debt will be more challenging and expensive.</p><p> About a fifth of all malls financed through commercial mortgage-backed securities are underwater, meaning the properties are worth less than the loans they back, said Kevin Fagan, head of commercial real-estate economic analysis for Moody&#39;s.</p><p> In some cases, they are worth a lot less. Crystal Mall&#39;s former owner, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SPG" class="">Simon Property Group</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> stopped making payments on $81 million in outstanding CMBS debt during the pandemic and last year handed back the keys to the property it had owned since 1999.</p><p> The loan—which was included in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/carl-icahn-placing-a-big-bet-against-mall-owners-11574201244?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the CMBX 6 index</a> shorted by famous investor Carl Icahn —is expected to liquidate at a $70 million loss, or about 87% of the outstanding balance, according to Moody&#39;s.</p><p> Similar stories are playing out across the country. In Indiana, Muncie Mall backs a $31 million loan but is worth only $6 million after a March appraisal, according to Trepp. The 52-year-old mall was appraised at $73 million nine years ago and nearly fully occupied as recently as 2018.</p><p> Woodbridge Center, a 1.1 million-square-foot mall in central New Jersey, was appraised at $86 million earlier this year, a 76% drop from its last prepandemic appraisal in 2014, according to Trepp. The mall is in foreclosure on two CMBS loans, with outstanding balances totaling nearly a quarter-billion dollars. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826219?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “We&#39;ve seen dozens and dozens of malls liquidated at losses or had their values cut,” said Manus Clancy, senior managing director at Trepp.</p><p> Not all malls are on the brink of disaster. Newer, well-located properties with strong tenant rosters are generating healthy foot traffic and returns for investors. But even these high-quality malls have declined in value by an estimated 50% since 2016, Tibone said, making malls one of the worst performing commercial real-estate sectors over that period.</p><p> Widespread <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retail-chains-shed-stores-but-it-isnt-good-for-business-11605436204?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">department-store closures</a> beginning in 2018 hastened malls&#39; decline. Large mall anchors like</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/M" class="">Macy&#39;s</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> Bon-Ton, JCPenney and Sears closed about 875 department stores between 2018 and the end of 2020, according to Green Street, compared with a combined 175 in 2016 and 2017.<p></p><p> “It really accelerated the death spiral of the industry,” Tibone said. “You start losing department stores, that causes sales and traffic at the center to decline. Then more tenants leave. It starts this awful cycle.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C72EA178-F0CA-46FE-B63D-3CE629CAF70C&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Flocal-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The pandemic has changed the way we shop. More people buying things online means more people returning things, too. WSJ&#39;s Dalvin Brown explains how some companies are leveraging gig workers to make those returns for you. Photo illustration: David Fang<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The death spiral at the Crystal Mall started in 2018, when anchor tenant <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sears-exit-would-leave-big-holes-in-malls-some-landlords-welcome-that-1539342000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Sears declared bankruptcy</a> and announced plans to close. Macy&#39;s shut its location three years later. Overall revenue at Crystal Mall declined 39% between 2018 and 2022, while expenses fell only 10%, according to Trepp.</p><p> “All the stores used to be open, and everything used to be nice and beautiful,” said Melissa Rodriguez, 40 years old, standing outside the mall&#39;s food court one recent afternoon.</p><p> Now, many of the shops have closed. One of her favorite stores, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BBBYQ" class="">Bed Bath &amp; Beyond</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> is shutting its location after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/some-investors-arent-giving-up-on-bed-bath-beyond-7c1dcd37?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">declaring bankruptcy</a> earlier this year. Before the pandemic, Rodriguez said, she often visited the mall twice a week but now comes only once a month.</p><p> “It&#39;s not like before,” she said.</p><p> Christmas Tree Shops, which shared an anchor space with Bed Bath &amp; Beyond, is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/christmas-tree-shops-to-liquidate-all-stores-ea53da39?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">also closing following bankruptcy</a> . Once those retailers vacate, JCPenney will be the only anchor tenant left at Crystal Mall. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823825?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Crystal Mall fell into decline following closings of two anchor stores, Sears and Macy&#39;s, in recent years.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Johnny Milano/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Brule, Waterford&#39;s first selectman, said he would like to see the property redeveloped into a mixed-use site. He envisions a hotel for tourists visiting nearby Mystic and housing for local firefighters and teachers as well as employees of the local submarine manufacturer, General Dynamics Electric Boat. Maybe a hockey rink or a bowling alley, somewhere for the town&#39;s teenagers to gather.</p><p> “That&#39;s what this property could be,” Brule said.</p><p> It is unlikely these dreams for Crystal Mall will be realized under its new owner, New York-based investment firm Namdar Realty Group. A company executive told Brule during an introductory call that it doesn&#39;t redevelop properties, Brule said.</p><p> Namdar Chief Executive Igal Namdar said the company plans to implement an “aggressive leasing strategy to attract a mix of national and local tenants” to Crystal Mall.</p><p> Write to Kate King at <a href="mailto:kate.king@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">kate.king@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d<author><![CDATA[Kate King]]></author><category> wsj-usnews</category><category> commercial re</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> Retail/Wholesale</category><category>混合零售</category><category>购物中心/超市</category><category>Real Estate Services/Transactions</category><category> Retail Real Estate</category><category> Commercial/Industrial Real Estate</category><category> Real Estate/Construction</category><category> Real Estate</category><category> Retail</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Commercial RE</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Moody&#39;s</category><category> MCO</category><category> Bed Bath &amp; Beyond</category><category> BBBYQ</category><category> Macy&#39;s</category><category> M</category><category> Simon Property Group</category><category> SPG</category><category> Kevin Fagan</category><category> Rob Brule</category><category> Carl Icahn</category><category> Vince Tibone</category><category> Manus Clancy</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>retail</category><category> wholesale</category><category>混合零售</category><category>购物广场</category><category>超市</category><category>real estate services</category><category> transactions</category><category> retail real estate</category><category> commercial</category><category> industrial real estate</category><category> real estate</category><category> construction </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Benefit of Owning Stocks Over Bonds Keeps Shrinking]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Some worry the rally is unsustainable after a gauge of stocks&#39; relative value falls to two-decade low <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001094270"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826395?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Analysts say the premium to own stocks over bonds can&#39;t stay this low indefinitely.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Julia Nikhinson/Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001094270"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sam-goldfarb" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sam Goldfarb</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-benefit-of-owning-stocks-over-bonds-keeps-shrinking-20528203"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The extra reward for holding stocks instead of bonds has fallen to its lowest level in 20 years, threatening a recent hot streak for major indexes.</p><p> One method for gauging the value of stocks is to compare their earnings yield—calculated by dividing a company&#39;s expected earnings over the next year by its stock price—to the yield on government bonds, considered the closest thing to a risk-free return. The difference, sometimes called the equity-risk premium, shows how much investors are being compensated for the additional risk of owning stocks.</p><p> And right now, that isn&#39;t much.</p><p> The gap between the earnings yield of the S&amp;P 500 and the yield on the 10-year US government bond dropped to around 1.1 percentage point last week, its narrowest since 2002. The spread to the yield on the 10-year Treasury inflation-protected security, seen by some analysts as the better benchmark because corporate earnings <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-is-inflation-so-sticky-it-could-be-corporate-profits-b78d90b7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">tend to adjust with inflation</a> , has similarly fallen to its lowest level since 2003, at around 3.5 percentage points.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What is your approach to stocks versus bonds?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> The risk premium first started shrinking in the second half of last year. In that period, stocks stabilized from an early year selloff, even as bond yields kept climbing in response to the Federal Reserve raising interest rates to fight inflation. This year, the premium <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stocks-havent-looked-this-unattractive-since-2007-78fc374c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has continued to dwindle</a> for slightly different reasons: Bond yields haven&#39;t risen as much, but stocks have taken flight—lifted by investors&#39; growing optimism about the economy.</p><p> Whatever happens to change it, there is a consensus on Wall Street that the equity-risk premium can&#39;t stay this low forever.</p><p> For stock prices relative to earnings to be back to where they were at the start of the 2022 selloff “when interest rates are 2x, 3x higher than they were really doesn&#39;t add up,” said Tim Urbanowicz, head of research and investment strategy at Innovator ETFs.</p><p> Investors and analysts also tend to agree that an ultralow risk premium doesn&#39;t mean that this year&#39;s stock rally has reached its conclusion.</p><p> For one thing, they point out, risk premiums have gotten much lower before—in the dot-com bubble of the late 1990s. Back then, the gap between the S&amp;P 500&#39;s earnings yield and inflation-adjusted, or “real,” Treasury yields briefly collapsed entirely, according to some measures. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826036?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Fed Chair Jerome Powell last week indicated another rate increase is possible but also signaled that rates could remain steady.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Al Drago/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Looking back at history, analysts say risk premiums revert to average over time—typically because prospects for corporate earnings dim, not because investors get frightened by valuations on their own.</p><p> “I haven&#39;t found a very strong statistical relationship between the earnings yield relative to the 10-year Treasury—whether it&#39;s real or nominal—and future returns over, say, a one- or three-year horizon,” said Brian Jacobsen, chief economist of Annex Wealth Management.</p><p> Investors have another source of hope: Risk premiums could normalize because bond yields fall rather than stock prices.</p><p> Stoking this optimism, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-25-2023/card/is-the-fed-prepping-its-final-interest-rate-hike--9HVDuRwso3GtKrz2IhkL?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">many believe that the Fed is finally done</a> raising short-term interest rates.</p><p> With inflation showing signs of cooling, interest-rate futures indicate that investors think there is only a slightly better than 30% chance that the Fed raises rates again this year, according to CME Group data. At a press conference Wednesday, Fed Chair Jerome Powell <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">left the door open to another rate increase</a> , but also indicated that the central bank could opt to leave rates steady for a while if economic data cooperated.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Yields on US Treasurys largely reflect investors&#39; expectations for short-term rates over the life of a bond. Even if the Fed has reached the end of its tightening campaign, bond yields could rise further if the central bank keeps rates at current levels for longer than investors anticipate.</p><p> Still, the consensus is that both rates and bond yields should eventually decline.</p><p> That view is embedded in current bond yields. As of Friday, the yield on the benchmark 10-year Treasury inflation-protected security was around 1.6%, according to Tradeweb. However, the five-year TIPS yield was 1.9%, implying that investors expect real short-term rates to be lower in the second half than in the first half of the next 10 years.</p><p> Meanwhile, most Fed officials estimated in June that real interest rates will eventually settle at a level no higher than 0.5%.</p><p> Jacobsen, of Annex Wealth Management, said he thinks the 10-year TIPS yield could fall to 0.75% or 1% over the next 12 to 18 months.</p><p> That would mean investors are rewarded more for owning stocks, assuming indexes don&#39;t rally much further. But it would also mean that bonds prices have climbed. Jacobsen said his team has recently recommended that clients move more money into bonds after previously tilting more heavily toward stocks.</p><p> “If you look at the hiking cycles from 1989 to the present, every time they hit the plateau for rates that was pretty bullish for bonds,” he said, “and we think we&#39;re at least close to that point.”</p><p> Write to Sam Goldfarb at <a href="mailto:sam.goldfarb@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sam.goldfarb@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e0815ea6-ecc0-4136-bdae-5d2167589c29.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-benefit-of-owning-stocks-over-bonds-keeps-shrinking-20528203</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-benefit-of-owning-stocks-over-bonds-keeps-shrinking-20528203<author><![CDATA[Sam Goldfarb]]></author><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>华尔街日报金融市场</category><category>Monetary Policy</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Equity Markets</category><category> Debt/Bond Markets</category><category> Commodity/Financial Market News</category><category> Government Debt/Bond Markets</category><category> National Government Debt/Bond Markets</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> monetary policy</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>equity markets</category><category> debt</category><category> bond markets</category><category> commodity</category><category> financial market news</category><category> government debt</category><category> national government debt</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Flirting With Danger’ Review: Heiress Undercover]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Marguerite Harrison was perfect for the job: beautiful, charming, intelligent, fluent in French and German, with an exceptionally good memory. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590108174236205124"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826380?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Marguerite Harrison during the filming of “Grass.”</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alamy Stock Photo </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590108174236205124"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Moira Hodgson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 30, 2023 4:12 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/flirting-with-danger-review-heiress-undercover-4c12601e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> In April 1920 a Baltimore heiress was arrested in Russia, accused of being a secret agent. Marguerite Harrison (1879-1967), whose wedding trousseau had numbered 40 outfits, now wore lice-infested clothes and a pair of men&#39;s shoes. Imprisoned without trial, she would spend 10 months in Moscow&#39;s notorious Lubyanka jail, including time in solitary confinement.</p><p> The daughter of a shipping magnate, Marguerite had grown up with all the trappings of her class: tutors, governesses, piano lessons, debutante balls and annual trips to Europe. She could have led a pleasant if uneventful life,punctuated by garden parties, games of bridge and nights at the opera. Instead, driven by an insatiable thirst for adventure and an almost pathological attraction to danger, she became a spy. She was perfect for the job: beautiful, charming, intelligent, fluent in French and German, with an exceptionally good memory. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/1f9e1d53-d9f2-4bac-a4b6-d1f795204366.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Her mother, Elizabeth, had hoped that Marguerite would marry a landed European aristocrat; those dreams were dashed when Marguerite fell in love with Tom Harrison, a man Elizabeth despised. Tom came from a prominent but penniless Baltimore family. The couple married in 1901 and had a son the next year. After Tom died of a brain tumor in 1915, Marguerite went to work at the Baltimore Sun as a society reporter, then as a cultural critic. When America joined World War I in 1917, she wrote patriotic stories to boost support. But she felt restless working in the newsroom and wanted to go to the front. In the fall of 1918, she volunteered to join Military Intelligence, using the newspaper as a cover.</p><p> The war ended in November, so she was sent to Paris to attend the peace talks. She proved to be a clever, politically astute reporter and, with her considerable social connections, a valuable intelligence officer. She was prescient about the effect the harsh armistice terms would have on Germany. She took mental notes and filed reports to Military Intelligence, dropping them off with contact agents in hotels or using a cipher book to send cables of coded messages.</p><p> In “Flirting With Danger: The Mysterious Life of Marguerite Harrison, Socialite Spy,” Janet Wallach presents a compelling story that pulsates with the energy of a thriller. She describes how Harrison, the first American woman to get into Germany after the armistice, found the country in shock. There were clashes between the Communist-leaning Spartacists and the right-wing Freikorps, a paramilitary group of former soldiers. Count Harry Kessler, a former German ambassador to Poland, summed up the situation: “The German people, starved and dying by the hundred thousand, were reeling deliriously between blank despair, frenzied revelry and Revolution. Berlin had become a nightmare, a carnival of jazz bands and rattling machine guns.” Harrison narrowly escaped being shot by crossfire in the street.</p><p> By her own admission, Harrison “was not a Marxist or even a Socialist.” Yet she wondered, Ms. Wallach tells us, whether the Bolsheviks “could provide some answers to the great unrest in the world.” Her great desire was to visit Russia. A visa was refused. Undaunted, in February 1920 she slipped across Poland&#39;s eastern border. In Moscow, the head of the foreign office seemed to accept her credentials as a journalist. He surprised her by saying he was glad about Prohibition in America. He believed that workers, unable to go to saloons and drink, would “flock to political meetings” instead, spreading the popularity of communism. Two months after that friendly encounter, Harrison was arrested. Thanks to a mole in the US intelligence service, the Russians had known about her for some time. To obtain her release, she agreed to remain in Moscow as a double agent.</p><p> Here the story gets murky. How much damage she inflicted is impossible to assess, but several of Harrison&#39;s acquaintances blamed her for their subsequent arrests. Nevertheless, before long, Harrison was back in the Lubyanka.</p><p> Ms. Wallach, whose previous books include “Desert Queen: The Extraordinary Life of Gertrude Bell” (1996) and “The Richest Woman in America: Hetty Green in the Gilded Age” (2012), relies heavily on Harrison&#39;s autobiography, “There&#39;s Always Tomorrow” (1935), and other books to tell her story. Harrison recounts her Russian experience in “Marooned in Moscow” (1921), an oddly dispassionate memoir. “The Liberation of Marguerite Harrison” (2020), a biography by Elizabeth Atwood, a former editor at the Baltimore Sun, is at times dubious of Harrison&#39;s accounts, noting that after she left Russia, she whitewashed her prison experiences.</p><p> Harrison was very much at home with the Russians, whether they were Communists or Czarists. “The unflappable newswoman who suppressed her feelings and admitted she &#39;felt afraid to form close ties,&#39; even with her young son, found the Russians&#39; exuberance irresistible,” Ms. Wallach writes. Among other things, Harrison loved their generosity and their “Oriental sense of hospitality.”</p><p> The Russian fiasco did not erode Harrison&#39;s self-confidence or her enthusiasm for danger. In 1923 she set off on a 46-day trek to make “Grass,” a documentary about the remote Bakhtiari tribe in present-day Iran. Each year about 5,000 Bakhtiaris and their 50,000 animals would make a procession through the treacherous mountain passes of southwest Persia in search of green pastures. Harrison stars in the film, directed by her friend Merian Cooper, who would later make “King Kong.” But “Grass” was a cover for an espionage mission. The Bakhtiari controlled land that had large reserves of oil.</p><p> Despite the occasional cliché and at times cloying prose (during her wedding, Harrison is said to have eyes that were “dancing like soft clouds in a dazzling sky”), Ms. Wallach tells a good story. Harrison&#39;s adventures over seven years—trips to the Baltics, China, Japan, Manchuria, Turkey and across Siberia—make for exciting reading. However, the woman herself proves elusive. Why was she driven to undertake such risks? She wasn&#39;t a zealot and doesn&#39;t seem to have had any strong political beliefs. So what motivated her? She is opaque, well used to hiding things. As Ms. Wallach writes, “spies have their own truths.”</p><p> <em>Ms. Hodgson is the author of “It Seemed Like a Good Idea at the Time: My Adventures in Life and Food.”</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 20:12:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/flirting-with-danger-review-heiress-undercover-4c12601e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/flirting-with-danger-review-heiress-undercover-4c12601e<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Arts Calendar: Happenings for the Week of July 30]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles try to come out of their shells, &#39;Back to the Future&#39; brings its flux capacitor to Broadway, Migos&#39; Quavo releases new music and more. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJO-0000022839"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825962?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Sigourney Weaver in &#39;The Lost Flowers of Alice Hart&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Amazon Studios</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJO-0000022839"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> WSJ Arts in Review Staff</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 30, 2023 5:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-30-airdigital-f1b1afee"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><h3>电影</h3><p>• <strong>“Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles: Mutant Mayhem”</strong> <em><strong>&nbsp;</strong> (Aug. 2)</em> : Cowabunga! Michelangelo, Donatello, Leonardo and Raphael are back at it, chowing down on pizza, fighting bruisers and trying to fit into the human world with the help of April in the latest installment of the classic franchise. Jeff Rowe directs the computer-animated film whose star-stuffed voice cast includes Hannibal Buress, John Cena, Jackie Chan, Ice Cube, Post Malone, Seth Rogen, Paul Rudd and Maya Rudolph.</p><p> • <strong>“Passages”</strong> <em>(Aug. 4)</em> : The latest from Ira Sachs (“Love Is Strange”) is a tangled romantic drama about a gay couple whose marriage is put in peril when one partner begins an affair with a younger woman. Franz Rogowski, Ben Whishaw and Adèle Exarchopoulos star.</p><p> • <strong>“Meg 2: The Trench”</strong> <em>(Aug. 4)</em> : Taking “don&#39;t go in the water” to epic proportions, the sequel to the campy summer film of 2018 has Jason Statham back in a wetsuit, fighting supersize aquatic terrors.</p><p> • <strong>“Corner Office”</strong> <em>(Aug. 4)</em> : An awkward new employee played by Jon Hamm discovers a secret room that helps him succeed in business—with and without really trying—in Joachim Back&#39;s dark comedy based on a short novel by Jonas Karlsson.</p><p> • <strong>“Shortcomings”</strong> <em>(Aug. 4)</em> : Randall Park (“Fresh Off the Boat”) makes his directorial debut with a dramedy, adapted from Adrian Tomine&#39;s graphic novel of the same name, about the ups and downs in the lives of three Bay Area residents.</p><h3> TV</h3><p> • <strong>“Dark Winds,” season 2</strong> <em>(AMC, July 30)</em> : The 1970s-set thriller based on the books by Tony Hillerman about Navajo police officers is back.</p><p> • <strong>“Run the Burbs”</strong> <em>(The CW, July 31)</em> : Created by Andrew Phung (“Kim&#39;s Convenience”) and Scott Townend, this Canadian comedy about a stay-at-home dad and his entrepreneurial wife makes its way to American screens.</p><p> • <strong>“Physical,” season 3</strong> <em>(Apple TV+, Aug. 2)</em> : After three seasons, Annie Weisman&#39;s drama set in the world of &#39;80s aerobics will hang up its leg warmers. This final sweat session finds Zooey Deschanel joining a cast that includes Rose Byrne, Rory Scovel and Paul Sparks.</p><p> • <strong>“The Big Nailed It Baking Challenge”</strong> <em>(Netflix, Aug. 4)</em> : Fans of failure and the culinarily challenged will both be familiar with “Nailed It!”—the competition show in which very amateur bakers try to re-create very complicated recipes. Hosts Nicole Byer and Jacques Torres</p> are back for this spinoff, featuring a season-long competition that gives the bakers a little professional help as they vie against one another for a cash prize.<p></p><p> • <strong>“The Lost Flowers of Alice Hart”</strong> <em>(Prime Video, Aug. 4)</em> : Sigourney Weaver and Alycia Debnam-Carey (“Fear the Walking Dead”) star in this Australian series, spanning many years, about an abused then orphaned girl who moves in with her grandmother and pieces together family secrets. Asher Keddie, Leah Purcell and Charlie Vickers are among the cast in Sarah Lambert&#39;s seven-part adaptation of Holly Ringland&#39;s novel.</p><h3> Theater</h3><p> • <strong>“Lets Call Her Patty”</strong> <em>(Lincoln Center Theater, Claire Tow Theater, New York, opens July 31)</em> : Rhea Perlman plays a comfortable Upper West Sider who looks to her niece ( Leslie Rodriguez Kritzer ) for help when her daughter ( Arielle Goldman ) quickly becomes a famous artist—then turns to drugs—in the new play by Zarina Shea, directed by Margot Bordelon.</p><p> • <strong>“Back to the Future: The Musical”</strong> <em>(Winter Garden Theatre, opens Aug. 3)</em> : Marty McFly and Doc Brown might not need roads, but they won&#39;t turn their noses up at Broadway. The classic 1980s sci-fi comedy gets a stage adaptation from its original creators, Bob Gale and Robert Zemeckis, and music from Grammy winners Alan Silvestri and Glen Ballard. Casey Likes and Roger Bart star in the John Rando -directed production.</p><h3>音乐</h3><p>• <strong>Mammoth WVH, “Mammoth II”</strong> <em>(Aug. 4)</em> : The rock project of Wolfgang Van Halen (scion of hard-rock icon Eddie Van Halen and</p> Valerie Bertinelli ) returns with its sophomore album. As he did on the first, Mr. Van Halen wrote and performed all the songs here, looking to create a heavier and more melodic record this time around.<p></p><p> • <strong>Miles Kane, “One Man Band”</strong> <em>(Aug. 4)</em> : Last Shadow Puppets frontman Miles Kane releases his fifth solo studio album, a stripped down, personal LP that the singer has said nods at the Strokes and the Libertines.</p><p> • <strong>Quavo, “Rocket Power”</strong> <em>(Aug. 4)</em> : The Migos cofounder is back with his second solo outing, the first music he&#39;s released since the 2022 killing of Migos member Takeoff. With a title that acknowledges Takeoff&#39;s own solo recording (“The Last Rocket”), the LP points in an emotional yet empowering direction. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="673" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825957?width=700&amp;height=673" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Arghavan Khosravi&#39;s &#39;The Battleground&#39; (2022)</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Rachel Uffner Gallery, NY</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>艺术</h3><p>• <strong>“Remedios Varo: Science Fictions”</strong> <em>(Art Institute of Chicago, July 29-Nov. 27)</em> : The Spanish-born Varo (1908-1963) fled Europe early in World War II—settling in Mexico City, meeting with both local and émigré artists there and developing a personal style that blended Surrealist elements with historic imagery. The first US show of her work since 2000, this display presents more than 20 paintings she created over the two decades before her death, along with selections from her archives—preparatory sketches, studies, notebooks, personal possessions and more—to offer a holistic view of her creative process.</p><p> • <strong>Intersect Aspen</strong> <em>(Aspen Ice Garden, Colorado, Aug. 1-4)</em> : While it might not be ski season, there are still reasons to hit the slopes. Aspen&#39;s only art and design fair returns for its third edition with several new galleries exhibiting and plenty of offsite events, including museum tours, studio visits and more.</p><p> • <strong>“Arghavan Khosravi: Black Rain”</strong> <em>(Rose Art Museum, Waltham, Mass., Aug 3-Oct. 22)</em> : When Iranian artist Arghavan Khosravi arrived in the US in 2015, she worked mostly on a small scale. Since then, her art has grown in size and scope, with her most impressive pieces incorporating painting, sculpture and collage. Drawing from classical Persian miniatures (several of which will also be on view), she explores the challenges faced by women under Iran&#39;s oppressive regime and the complications of being a Muslim in America. Now she&#39;s receiving her first comprehensive museum survey.</p><p> • <strong>“Sitting on Chrome: Mario Ayala, rafa esparza, and Guadalupe Rosales”</strong> <em>(San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, Aug. 3-Feb. 19, 2024)</em> : These artists use the lowrider as a source of inspiration for a collaborative exhibition that features a mural by all three of them, a series of multisensory installations, and works that include painting, sculpture, photography and more.</p><h3> Last Call</h3><p> • <strong><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/parade-review-a-broadway-musical-of-american-bigotry-fbfa32a6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“Parade”</a></strong> <em>(Bernard B. Jacobs Theatre, New York, closes Aug. 6)</em> : Ben Platt stars in a revival of Alfred Uhry and Jason Robert Brown&#39;s show about Leo Frank, a Jewish factory superintendent in Atlanta who was lynched after being wrongly convicted of the murder of a 13-year-old girl in 1913.</p><p> For additional Arts Calendar listings visit wsj.com. Write to brian.kelly@wsj.com and julia.fischer@wsj.com.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 09:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-30-airdigital-f1b1afee</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-30-airdigital-f1b1afee<category> arts in review</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Celebrities</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>音乐</category><category>Theater</category><category> Television/Radio</category><category> Calendar of Events</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>IWE Filter</category><category> Routine General News</category><category> Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> art</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>celebrities</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>music</category><category> theater</category><category> television</category><category> radio</category><category> calendar of events</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>iwe filter</category><category> routine general news </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Robert Motherwell: Pure Painting’ Review: Giving Form to an Abstractionist’s Career]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The painter&#39;s retrospective at the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth examines his life&#39;s work while trying to explain his place in the postwar scene. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12351792199352413568404590060251464088246"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825810?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Installation view of &#39;Robert Motherwell: Pure Painting&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: The Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12351792199352413568404590060251464088246"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Peter Plagens</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 29, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/robert-motherwell-pure-painting-review-giving-form-to-an-abstractionists-career-5432846d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <em>Fort Worth, Texas</em></p><p> <strong>&#39;Among the advanced</strong> American artists of his generation, the abstract painter Robert Motherwell (1915-1991) was also the most deeply grounded in European culture,” writes Jack Flam, director of the Dedalus Foundation that Motherwell founded to support an appreciation of modern art, in the catalog of a new exhibition here. Considered either the youngest of the first-generation Abstract Expressionists or the oldest of its second-generation cohort, Motherwell was the most academically educated of them. He earned a bachelor&#39;s degree in philosophy at Stanford, then undertook graduate studies in philosophy at Harvard, followed by graduate coursework in art history at Columbia. He also edited an authoritative anthology of the Dada painters and poets. Understandably, as Mr. Flam notes, Motherwell “advocated for paintings that were abstract but not necessarily nonobjective”—meaning that although they weren&#39;t representational in the conventional sense, they somehow alluded, if only in their titles, to things and events in the real world.</p><p> The new retrospective curated by Susan Davidson (with an unlikely subtitle, given the above)—“Robert Motherwell: Pure Painting,” at the cavernous Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth—covers the artist&#39;s 50-year career as a painter, which began in 1939 and ended only with his death. It contains 56 works, 30 of them giant canvases approaching the size of murals. Except for the inclusion of a few painted words, Motherwell&#39;s oeuvre is entirely abstract. The question lurking in this stately exhibition is: How good a painter, both historically and aesthetically, was Motherwell? “Pure Painting” answers the question with, in effect, a verdict of very, very good, often great, but on occasion somewhat precious or grandiloquent. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="527" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825789?width=700&amp;height=527" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Motherwell&#39;s &#39;Elegy to the Spanish Republic&#39; (c. 1962/82)</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Dedalus Foundation / ARS, NY</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Motherwell traveled to Europe early and often, and he absorbed the modernist lessons of everyone from Matisse to Mondrian. He was most attracted to Surrealism, however—not the hand-painted, realistic dream paintings of Salvador Dalí, but rather the unconscious “automatic writing” approach to art espoused by the poet André Breton and his circle. Motherwell&#39;s leftist politics (the catalog says he considered “the tragedy of the Spanish Republic [and its defeat by Franco] as emblematic of the idea of tragedy in our time”) were ubiquitous among modernists of his era.</p><p> Couple Motherwell&#39;s attempt to balance improvisation and just-rightness with his politics and you have “The Little Spanish Prison” (1941-44), a deceptively profound abstraction of a cell&#39;s bars. Employing that same sensibility in sweeping painterly gestures—the New York School&#39;s grandchild of automatic writing—Motherwell gives us his magnificent black-and-white “Elegy to the Spanish Republic” series. He painted more than 100 of them from 1948 to 1990 and—crisp, symbolically durable, and visually hard to forget—they are Motherwell&#39;s most memorable paintings. “Unlike the rest of my work,” Motherwell once said, “the Elegies are, for the most part, public statements.” He meant that the works are, pictorially, as overtly political as he ever got.</p><p> In 1945 Motherwell signed a contract, which included a monthly stipend in return for a rather hefty 75 works a year, with the then-cutting-edge Samuel Kootz Gallery in New York. (He&#39;d had his first gallery exhibition in 1939 in Paris.) By 1960—after many shows at any number of galleries, including his first retrospective, at hyper-progressive Bennington College in Vermont—Motherwell was able to quit his teaching job at Hunter College and live from the sales of his paintings alone.</p><p> Motherwell&#39;s personal life was fluctuant. He was married four times, the first to Maria Emilia Ferreira y Moyers, whom he met on a ship bound for Mexico. When Motherwell went to Reno, Nev., where he was being sued by Maria for divorce due to his heavy drinking (a lifelong problem), he met Betty Little, whom he subsequently wed and with whom he had two daughters. In 1957, after seven years of matrimony, Betty and the children moved out. A year later, Motherwell married the abstract painter Helen Frankenthaler ; their artistically beneficial union survived for a dozen years. Finally, he married German-American photographer Renate Ponsold, a marriage that lasted until Motherwell&#39;s death. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="308" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825792?width=700&amp;height=308" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Motherwell&#39;s &#39;Summer Open With Mediterranean Blue&#39; (1974)</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Dedalus Foundation / ARS, NY</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In 1967, Motherwell traced the physical outline of a smaller painting leaning against a larger one. The minimalist drawing constituted an upside-down “U” that Motherwell subsequently turned back to right side up. Out of this somewhat Dada-like coincidence came the artist&#39;s second-most well-known group of paintings, the “Open” series, which the catalog says “grew out of Motherwell&#39;s desire to achieve a kind of Zen-like austerity.” While they carry the artist&#39;s characteristic compositional élan and delicate touch, and the monochrome canvases—mainly blue, orange, or ocher—are elegant, the “Open” paintings seem more self-conscious than passionate.</p><p> The observation—which nowadays amounts to an indictment—that, as the catalog puts it, “Motherwell articulated a male-dominated, Euro-North American, and generally white aesthetic canon” might be true. But it&#39;s close to meaningless; every artist articulates his or her own cultural and artistic grounding. A bit more telling is the observation in Artforum in 1965 by the painter and critic Sidney Tillim that Motherwell&#39;s work “comes too late to be topical, too soon to be historical”—that is, his paintings are neither groundbreaking Abstract Expressionism in the manner of Jackson Pollock or Barnett Newman,</p> nor removed chronologically enough to constitute a commentary on them. Nevertheless, the “Open” series and “Elegy” paintings, along with several additional autonomous works, make this retrospective well worth seeing—preferably more than once.<p></p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Plagens is an artist and writer in Connecticut.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/robert-motherwell-pure-painting-review-giving-form-to-an-abstractionists-career-5432846d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/robert-motherwell-pure-painting-review-giving-form-to-an-abstractionists-career-5432846d<category> arts in review</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Modernist/Postmodernist Art</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> art</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>modernist</category><category> postmodernist art</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Soundies: The Ultimate Collection’ Review: Musical Windows on the World War II Homefront]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A four-disc Blu-ray set compiles hundreds of the three-minute films from the 1940s, which played on jukebox-like Panorams and featured music, dancing and stars like Nat King Cole and Doris Day early in their careers. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590114891616948902"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825711?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ben Webster playing sax in &#39;Hot Chocolate (Cottontail)&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Kino Lorber </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590114891616948902"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Will Friedwald</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 29, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/soundies-the-ultimate-collection-review-musical-windows-on-the-world-war-ii-homefront-94845ddc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Who knew that we were loving Soundies for all these years for the wrong reason?</p><p> Even those who don&#39;t know they are called “Soundies” are probably familiar with at least some of the films themselves. The name refers to about 1,800 three-minute musical films produced from 1940 to 1947. These were originally exhibited on a Panoram, a curious hybrid machine, which combined a 16mm projection system and a screen with a jukebox mechanism. Manufactured and distributed by the Mills Novelty Co. in Chicago, these devices were found in saloons and restaurants across the country.</p><p> Soundies were omnipresent during the World War II era, then they disappeared for roughly three decades but began to be seen again in the early years of home video—which coincided with the birth of MTV, a descendant of the Soundies concept. For the past 40 years or so, dozens if not hundreds of these remarkable shorts have been readily viewable, first on VHS tapes and eventually, in the 21st century, all over YouTube, where individual films—and the medium as a whole—have elicited millions of views.</p><p> And now we are experiencing something of a major Soundies renaissance. In 2021, Indiana University Press published Susan Delson&#39;s groundbreaking study “Soundies and the Changing Image of Black Americans on Screen.” A few months ago, Mark Cantor&#39;s meticulously detailed history and filmography “The Soundies—A History and Catalog of Jukebox Film Shorts of the 1940s” (I wrote one of the forewords) was published by McFarland &amp; Co. But the really big news is “Soundies: The Ultimate Collection,” the most ambitious home-video package yet of the films themselves. This four-disc Blu-ray set just released by Kino Lorber contains 200 individual Soundies, a deluxe 44-page booklet with essays by Ms. Delson, Mr. Cantor and Ellen C. Scott, an academic specializing in African-American cultural history, and copious commentary features.</p><p> For so long, Soundies fans have been forced to tolerate prints in ratty condition, so these beautiful restorations are a revelation. “Hot Chocolate (Cottontail)” may be the most valuable Soundie of them all—we have Duke Ellington&#39;s greatest-ever orchestra with Ben Webster playing a tenor saxophone solo that changed the course of the instrument, as well as a jitterbug exhibition by Whitey&#39;s Lindy Hoppers, including the peerless dancers Frankie Manning and Norma Miller. The print here is crystal clear and spectacular, clearly taken from a mint-condition 35mm original. It never looked so good, even to audiences in 1942.</p><p> This is an essential set in terms of both quality and quantity, with no shortage of amazing performances to enjoy and discuss. The most radical aspects of the package are its emphasis on black performers and its thematic organization largely along social, racial, political and gender lines.</p><p> The booklet essays make a compelling case for Soundies as a vehicle for African-American talent. In her book, Ms. Delson lists 300 “Black Cast” Soundies shorts, more than any other specialty group. But, more important, these films overwhelmingly present a positive image of African-American life in the &#39;40s. She convincingly argues that Soundies are much more enlightened than the Hollywood films of the period, depicting prosperous and stylish black families and comparatively few racial stereotypes.</p><p> Other ethnic and musical genres are also heavily represented in this package, including extensive amounts of rumba, conga, country and more. There are segments of the package devoted to all of these, as well as others structured along such lines as “Jumping Into Gender Play,” “Going to War,” “On the Job” and “The Home Front.” Every kind of music is accompanied by dancing; the set is easily worth the asking price for that footage alone.</p><p> There are cameo appearances by future celebrities, like a 23-year-old Nat King Cole playing piano and singing with his classic trio; Doris Day and Dorothy Dandridge, both at 19; and a pianist at a point so early in his career that he is billed as Walter Liberace,</p> offering a Chopinesque variation on “Tiger Rag.”<p></p><p> The films here are a glorious cross-section of popular music and jazz during World War II. Mr. Cantor notes that it was the war that made Soundies feasible—it was a time when millions of Americans were working in defense plants and gathering in local taverns for after-hours recreation. (Appropriately, the current package includes a whole set of songs about drinking.) The end of the war brought an end to all this outside-of-the-home fraternization, even before the rise of television.</p><p> In the &#39;80s, it was considered appropriate to describe Soundies as the forerunner of MTV music videos. With the benefit of time, we now know that they were much more than that—an invaluable musical and visual record of who we are as a people and a culture.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Friedwald writes about music and popular culture for the Journal and is the author of the newly published “Straighten Up and Fly Right: The Life and Music of Nat King Cole.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/soundies-the-ultimate-collection-review-musical-windows-on-the-world-war-ii-homefront-94845ddc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/soundies-the-ultimate-collection-review-musical-windows-on-the-world-war-ii-homefront-94845ddc<category> arts in review</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Doris Day</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>music</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item></channel></rss>